    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1971-01-07T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1971-01-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="48"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d48">
                <head>48. Action Memorandum From <persName type="from">Richard T. Kennedy</persName>
                    of the National Security Council Staff to the President’s Assistant for National
                    Security Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_KHA1" type="to"
                        >Kissinger</persName>)<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d48fn1">Source:
                        National Archives, <persName corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName> Presidential
                        Materials, <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files, Agency Files, Box 196,
                            <gloss target="#t_AID1">AID</gloss> 1/1/71-12/31/71. Top Secret;
                        Sensitive; Urgent. This copy of <persName corresp="#p_KDM1"
                            >Kennedy</persName>’s memorandum is on White House stationery, but
                            <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> and <persName
                            corresp="#p_KDM1">Kennedy</persName> were both in San Clemente, as was
                            <gloss target="#t_OMB1">OMB</gloss> Director <persName corresp="#p_SGP1"
                            >Shultz</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>San Clemente</placeName>, <placeName>California</placeName>,
                            <date calendar="gregorian" when="1971-01-07">January 7,
                        1971</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_MAP1">MAP</gloss> and <gloss target="#t_FMS1">FMS</gloss>,
                        1972</item>
                </list>
                <p>Wayne Smith called to give you the latest status on the <gloss target="#t_OMB1"
                        >OMB</gloss> budget recommendations. Referring to <ref target="#pg_7">page
                        7</ref> of his memorandum attached,<note n="2" xml:id="d48fn2">
                        <ref target="#d46">Document 46</ref>.</note> the revised figures are as
                    shown:</p>
                <table cols="5" rows="7">
                    <row role="label">
                        <cell/>
                        <cell>State/Defense <gloss target="#t_MAP1">MAP</gloss> Request</cell>
                        <cell>Original <gloss target="#t_OMB1">OMB</gloss> Recommendation</cell>
                        <cell>Revised <gloss target="#t_OMB1">OMB</gloss>
                        </cell>
                        <cell>HAK Recommendation<note n="3" xml:id="d48fn3">
                                <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> wrote in the
                                figures in this column. Above the column, <persName
                                    corresp="#p_KDM1">Kennedy</persName> wrote on January 7: “Called
                                to Wayne Smith.” See also <ref target="#d48fn5">footnote 5</ref>
                                below.</note>
                        </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Taiwan</cell>
                        <cell role="num">$25</cell>
                        <cell role="num">$15</cell>
                        <cell role="num">$20</cell>
                        <cell role="num">$25</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Greece</cell>
                        <cell role="num">25</cell>
                        <cell role="num">15</cell>
                        <cell role="num">15</cell>
                        <cell role="num">25</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Turkey</cell>
                        <cell role="num">130</cell>
                        <cell role="num">90</cell>
                        <cell role="num">100</cell>
                        <cell role="num">100</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Jordan</cell>
                        <cell role="num">50</cell>
                        <cell role="num">30</cell>
                        <cell role="num">45</cell>
                        <cell role="num">45</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Indonesia</cell>
                        <cell role="num">13</cell>
                        <cell role="num">13</cell>
                        <cell role="num">25</cell>
                        <cell role="num">25</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Ethiopia</cell>
                        <cell role="num">13</cell>
                        <cell role="num">12</cell>
                        <cell role="num">13</cell>
                        <cell role="num">13</cell>
                    </row>
                </table>
                <p>The rationale for the <gloss target="#t_OMB1">OMB</gloss> recommendations (with
                    which Smith agrees subject to your approval) is as follows:<note n="4"
                        xml:id="d48fn4">At the end of the memorandum <persName corresp="#p_KDM1"
                            >Kennedy</persName> wrote on January 8: “I subsequently mentioned to HAK
                        the fact that <gloss target="#t_MAP1">MAP</gloss> contingency fund request
                        had been raised from $15 to $100 million—thus the levels were not frozen
                        should needs arise later in the year. HAK said he wants to hold firm on the
                        $25 million for Taiwan and prefers $25 million for Greece though would not
                        fight to the death on the Greece figure.”</note>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Taiwan</hi>. State urges the additional funds because of the
                    possible foreign policy problems which may arise. <gloss target="#t_OMB1"
                        >OMB</gloss> has raised its original recommendation by $5 million. The total
                    of <gloss target="#t_MAP1">MAP</gloss> and <gloss target="#t_FMS1">FMS</gloss>
                    is equal to the total of $65 million requested by State and Defense. <gloss
                        target="#t_OMB1">OMB</gloss> adds $5 million to <gloss target="#t_FMS1"
                        >FMS</gloss> and reduces <gloss target="#t_MAP1">MAP</gloss> by $5 million
                    because Taiwan is flush with cash reserves and in a position to buy.<note n="5"
                        xml:id="d48fn5">At the bottom of the first page of the memorandum, <persName
                            corresp="#p_HBMJ1">Haig</persName> (presumably at some later date in
                        Washington) wrote: “<persName corresp="#p_HBMJ1">Haig</persName>/HAK
                            <persName corresp="#p_SGP1">Shultz</persName> 8 Jan phoncon,” drew a
                        line to the Taiwan and Greece rows in the table, and wrote to the right of
                            <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>’s “$25” entries, “Now
                        20.”</note>
                </p>
                <pb facs="0142" n="116" xml:id="pg_116"/>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Greece</hi>. Again the total <gloss target="#t_MAP1"
                        >MAP</gloss> and <gloss target="#t_FMS1">FMS</gloss> equals the $60 million
                    requested by State and Defense. <gloss target="#t_OMB1">OMB</gloss> however puts
                    more in <gloss target="#t_FMS1">FMS</gloss> and less in <gloss target="#t_MAP1"
                        >MAP</gloss> because Greece is flush with cash reserves and can buy (they
                    cite purchases of aircraft from France, for example).</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Turkey</hi>. For the past five years <gloss target="#t_MAP1"
                        >MAP</gloss> for Turkey has run between $90 and $95 million. <gloss
                        target="#t_OMB1">OMB</gloss> and Smith believe Turkey cannot absorb more
                    than $100 million in <gloss target="#t_MAP1">MAP</gloss>. There also is $10
                    million in <gloss target="#t_FMS1">FMS</gloss> (for a total of $110
                    million).</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Jordan</hi>. State and <gloss target="#t_DOD1">DOD</gloss>
                    originally requested $30 million. <gloss target="#t_OMB1">OMB</gloss> agreed to
                    this level. The latest State-Defense request is $50 million. There is no
                    definitive estimate on which this is based. <gloss target="#t_OMB1">OMB</gloss>
                    is willing to increase from $30 to a total of $45 million.</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Ethiopia</hi>. <gloss target="#t_OMB1">OMB</gloss> agrees with
                    State’s strong request for a total of $13 million.</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Indonesia</hi>. <gloss target="#t_OMB1">OMB</gloss> has put in
                    $25 million per our request.</p>
                <p>If you wish any changes we should get them to <gloss target="#t_OMB1">OMB</gloss>
                    today since Budget is going to press tonight. Smith believes the latest <gloss
                        target="#t_OMB1">OMB</gloss> proposals (the revised <gloss target="#t_OMB1"
                        >OMB</gloss> column) will do the job. You might wish to talk to Mr.
                        <persName>Packard</persName> about this to be sure that no wires are
                    crossed.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
